In the course of reviewing our procedures and rules, we identified in 1995 several measures to further improve safety at the facility:

1.    Expand the written procedure for 55-gallon drum handling and storage to include transfer to the pumping station
2.    Improve the design of the spill containment trenches and sump;
3.    Develop a specific written procedure to ensure against spills during maintenance of the HF transfer pump;
4.    Re-designing the tanker truck access to the storage tank to reduce the chance of vehicle accidents;
5.    Increase the separation between the HF storage tank and flammable chemicals.

All of these recommendations have either been implemented or are still being examined. Chem-tronics believes these improvements, in conjunction with our existing safety program, provide safe, effective conditions for the use of HF.

In 2003 numerous formal and informal reviews of the acid handling systems occurred.  As a result the tanker truck unloading procedures were modified and the employee Personal Protective Equipment plan was upgraded.  Recent developments in technology have resulted in improved gaskets for HF valve systems.  The HF valves are currently being replaced by valves with the new gasket material.  The facility has also decided that using 49% HF is safer than 70% HF.  The facility is currently switching over to this less concentrated material.  Final conversion to 49% HF is expected by fall of 2004.
